    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-10T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-10T09:00:00-05:00" n="386"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d386">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A Recruiting/209: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Union of South Africa</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Keena</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Capetown</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-10T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 10, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 10—2:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. I have been requested by the Prime Minister to inquire into the possibility
                    of obtaining the services of American doctors and nurses for hospital work
                    principally in Natal.</p>
                <p>Under the present arrangements the sick and wounded from North Africa and the
                    eastern Mediterranean area will be sent to Natal for hospitalization. The
                    operation of this plan is only just beginning but General Smuts<note n="9a"
                        xml:id="d386fn9a">Jan Christian Smuts, Prime Minister of the Union of South
                        Africa.</note> informs me that they are already encountering a serious
                    shortage of doctors and trained nurses.</p>
                <p>General Smuts suggested that possibly an American Red Cross corps could be formed
                    in the United States and sent to South Africa to aid in this emergency.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Keena</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
